# TypeScript Project Conventions

## Naming

| Construct | Convention | Example |
|-----------|-----------|---------|
| Variables, functions, parameters | `camelCase` | `testCount`, `parseTrxXml` |
| Interfaces & types | `PascalCase` (no `I` prefix) | `TestResult`, `FilterResult` |
| Enums & enum members | `PascalCase` | `TestState.Passed` |
| Constants | `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` or `camelCase` | `MAX_RETRIES`, `defaultTimeout` |
| Private fields | prefix with `_` | `_disposables` |
| Boolean variables | use `is`, `has`, `can`, `should` | `isRunning`, `hasChildren` |

## Types

- **Never use `any`**. Use `unknown` + type guards when the type is truly unknown.
- **Use explicit return types** on exported functions. Inferred types are fine for local helpers.
- **Prefer `interface`** for object shapes. Use `type` for unions, intersections, and mapped types.

## Null & Undefined

- Use **`undefined`** (not `null`) as the default "no value". Use `null` only when an external API requires it.
- Mark optional properties with `?` rather than `| undefined`.

## Collections

- Use **`Map`** and **`Set`** for key-value lookups and uniqueness — not plain objects.
- Use **`.some()`** or **`.find()`** instead of `.filter().length > 0`.
- Prefer **`for...of`** for side-effect iteration. Use `.map`/`.filter` for transforms.

## Modules

- Group imports: Node built-ins → external packages → internal modules, separated by blank lines.
- Export only what is needed — keep internal helpers unexported.
